<h1>Latest news 17-12-2023</h1>


 <h2>NuTyX 23.12.0 available with cards 2.7.2</h2>
  <p>
   Spiky and me are happy to announce the new version of NuTyX 23.12.0 and cards 2.7.2 .

 <h2>Fixed bugs</h2>
  <p>
   <table width="60%" cellspacing="0">
    <tr>
     <td>
      cards list -p doesn't display any version-release info.
     </td>
     <td>
      Fixed
     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      cards info -p &lt;package_name&gt; displays no info.
     </td>
     <td>
      Fixed
     </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      install-nutyx -ec mounts the folders each time the command is run.
      You end up with the same setup several times.
     </td>
     <td>
      Fixed
     </td>
    </tr>
  </table>

 <h2>Updated packages</h2>
 <p>
   SysV in 3.06 and systemd in 253.0 .
  <p>
   The xorg-server graphics server version 21.1.10,
   the Mesa 3D library in 23.2.1, Gtk4 4.12.4
   and Qt 6.6.1.
  <p>
   <ul>
    <li>
     The nvidia driver is update to version  535.129.03 .
    <li>
     The legacy driver 470.xx series in version 470.223.02 .
    <li>
     The legacy driver 390.xx series in version 390.157.13 .
   </ul>
  <p>
   The python interpreter is updated to version 3.11.6.
  <p>
   The XFCE desktop environment is updated to version 4.18.3.
  <p>
   The MATE desktop environment is a 1.26.2 version .
  <p>
   The GNOME desktop environment is also updated to version 45.2
   <p>
   The KDE desktop environment is available in Plasma 5.27.10, Framework 5.112.0
   and applications in 23.08.4.
  <p>
   Available browsers are: Firefox 120.0.1, Epiphany 45.1, etc
  <p>
   Many desktop applications have been updated as well like Telegram-desktop 4.12.2,
   Thunderbird 115.5.2, Scribus 1.5.8, Libreoffice 7.6.3.2, Gimp 2.10.36, etc.
  <p>
   Core NuTyX ships with Long Term Support (LTS) kernels:
   4.14.333, 4.19.302, 5.4.264, 5.10.204, 5.15.143, 6.1.68
   and the latest stable version 6.5.13.
  <p>
   The kernel change logs are available here:
  <p>
  <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v4.x/ChangeLog-4.14.333">kernel 4.14.333 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v4.x/ChangeLog-4.19.302">kernel 4.19.302 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/ChangeLog-5.4.264">kernel 5.4.264 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/ChangeLog-5.10.204">kernel 5.10.204 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/ChangeLog-5.15.143">kernel 5.15.143 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v6.x/ChangeLog-6.1.68">kernel 6.1.68 changelog</a>
  <p>
   <a href="https://cdn.kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v6.x/ChangeLog-6.5.13">kernel 6.5.13 changelog</a>
  <p>
   A BASE ISO (proposed in command line interface edition only without graphical interface).
  <p>
   13 desktops are now available in:
   XORG,
   OPENBOX,
   LXDE,
   XFCE4,
   JWM,
   CDE,
   LXQT,
   ENLIGHTENMENT,
   MATE,
   CINNAMON,
   BUDGIE,
   GNOME,
   KDE5.
  <p>
   They are available on the <a href="downloads">download page.</a>

 <h2>Upgrade process</h2>
  <p>
   A simple:
 </p><pre class="command_user"><kbd>sudo cards upgrade</kbd></pre>
   will make it.

 <h2>Thanks</h2>
  <p>
   With Thanks to the BLFS Team which helped out with a few problems we encountered.
  <p>
   Thanks to Spiky for his patience and his generosity in upgrading all thoses many packages.
  <p>
   Thanks to all you guys that have giving us positive or negative feedbacks about the distribution.

